The proposal aims to observe emission lines from hot cores, whose source size is typically ~0.1 pc. At the distance of the LMC, 0.1 pc corresponds to 0.4”. We thus request the resolution of 0.4” for band 6 and 7 in order to spatially resolve emission from hot cores. Since the targets are expected to be almost a point source, we do not need to use the ACA. 

Correlator Setup
We observe the CH3OH J = 5-4 and J = 7-6 transitions for identifications of hot cores. For this purpose, we use two spectral setups (band 6 and 7) for each target. A band 6 setup include the CH3OH J = 5-4 lines and a band 7 setup includes J = 7-6 lines. Many other lines are observed simultaneously and they are necessary to discuss the chemical compositions of observed hot cores. 
A line width of the methanol is typically 5--8 km/s toward Galactic hot cores. Other target lines are generally broader than the methanol lines. Thus, the velocity resolution of 1--2 km/s is sufficient for the detection. For the weak lines or in the case that S/N is low, we smooth the observed spectrum by binning data points to increase S/N. 
We estimate a source velocity of each target by using the previous CO (1-0) survey data of the LMC (Ref. MAGMA, Wong et al. 2011). Our targets have a recession velocity of 230 to 280 km/s. We here adopt a median value of target’s source velocity, 250 km/s. This is similar to the empirical recession velocity of the LMC (235 km/s). A slight change of sky frequencies for each target does not affect observations of the target lines since the requested bandwidth is wide enough. 

Calibration
We do not request special calibrations. 

Scheduling/time constraints
The proposed observations are not time-constrained. 

Other comments
An effect of shadowing is negligible for the declination of the LMC and for the expected array configuration. 
