    <prp:abstract>
A goal of this proposal is, (i) to identify hot cores for the first time in the Large Magellanic Cloud (LMC), and (ii) to unveil chemical compositions of hot cores in the LMC and to understand them in relation to its characteristic environment. 

We observe circumstellar materials around extragalactic young stellar objects (YSOs) to understand which environmental factors of galaxies are crucial for the chemical processes in molecular clouds. The LMC is the nearest extragalaxy with metal-poor environment. We propose ALMA band 6 and 7 observations of methanol and other chemically important species toward six hot core candidates in the LMC. Our previous infrared studies identified a number of embedded high-mass YSOs in the LMC and discovered that there is a systematic difference in the chemical compositions of ices between the LMC and the Milky Way. It is therefore anticipated that the environmental differences as well as unique ice chemistry in the LMC should cause different chemical processes in hot cores. 

With the FIRST detection of hot cores in the LMC, the proposed project will make a pioneering step of radioastronomical study of extragalactic hot cores with ALMA. </prp:abstract>
